Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Cut @sweet potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch cubes. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with @dukkah{1%tablespoon}/2, a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon}, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast in oven until sweet potato is tender and dukkah is golden brown, ~{20-25%minutes}, tossing halfway through.

Zest and halve @lime{1}. Mix @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, a pinch of lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice in a #small bowl{}. Season with salt and pepper. Stir in @water{1%tsp} to thin. TIP: Add a splash more water if crema still seems thick—it should have a drizzly, saucy consistency.

With your hand on top of one @chicken breasts{12%ounce}, cut ¾ of the way through, parallel to the #cutting board{}, stopping before you slice it completely. Open up chicken like a book, cover with #plastic wrap{}, and pound with a #mallet{} or #heavy pan{} until ½ inch thick. Repeat with other breast. Season all over with salt, pepper, and remaining dukkah.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook until no longer pink in center and dukkah is browned but not burnt, ~{3-4%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and set aside to rest.

Heat another drizzle of olive oil in same pan over medium heat. Add @sugar snap peas{6%ounce} and toss until tender and lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide sweet potatoes between plates, then top with chicken and snap peas. Drizzle with citrus crema and serve.